outlet: Anytime Fitness Ang Mo Kio South
author: Sihan Goi
text: Came here for a lunchtime workout at around 1230pm and it was quite quiet, with 2 staff at the door. The gym is quite small, though there are 2 levels. The bottom level has 2 squat racks with attached platforms, 2 Eleiko competition PL bars, 3 hybrid bars that spin quite well, 2 sets of colour bumper plates, more rubberized plates, a smith machine, cardio equipment, and cable machines. The platform area is very cramped, and it looks like they barely squeezed everything there, so you people who wish to access the stairs that side will need to step over the platform. Upstairs, there's a studio for stretching, dumbbells up to 50kg and benches, some other machines, and bathrooms. All in all, the equipment and facilities are quite new and clean and the crowd wasn't that much (perhaps because it was raining). Service was also pretty good - I left my water and shaker bottles there after training and was able to WhatsApp them with prompt replies, and was able to pick them up later in the day.

Plus the ladies washroom has sanitary pads which is +1000 aura points cause I actually had my period and needed it badly oops-. And they have deodorants here for everyone too.

The only downside is that its slightly cramp as all the machines are super close to each other and very little walking space. So if you come during peak hour and hate crowd, you gonna have a tough time, especially at the deadlift area.

Essentially, its a hidden gem if u come in the middle of the night (11pm+) and love feelin fancyü§©

author: Pushpendra Thakur
text:
Dear Team,

I‚Äôve been noticing a growing issue that‚Äôs affecting many serious members‚Äô workout experience:
A number of younger gym-goers often occupy machines for long periods, doing only one rep, then resting for 2‚Äì3 minutes, adding more weight, and repeating the same with minimal actual training volume.

This behavior not only limits access for others but also disrupts the flow during busy hours. Many of these users seem more focused on ego lifting or social media clips than productive workouts.

Suggestions:
‚Ä¢ Kindly have trainers monitor equipment usage during peak times
‚Ä¢ Display reminders on proper gym etiquette (e.g., time limits per machine during rush hours)
‚Ä¢ Educate new lifters on structured workout sets, reps, and rest intervals

We all start somewhere ‚Äî but the gym should also be a space of mutual respect and serious training. I hope management can take steps to maintain a more focused and respectful gym environment.

Thanks for your attention.

‚Äî A regular, respectful member

text:
This relatively new gym is well-maintained and very clean, with polite and attentive staff.

I personally prefer AF outlets that use the Hammer Strength/ Life Fitness brands of equipment, and was glad to note that this was the case here. There are toilets on both the first and second floors, which is convenient.

I felt that the first floor was rather cramped with machines and racks/platforms in close proximity to each other, and would urge gym users to be mindful of their surroundings especially when racking/removing weight plates. The low ceiling also made it feel a tad claustrophobic.

The second floor is a lot more roomy, though - chest day gymbros would particularly appreciate the spacious dumbbell area and multiple benches upstairs!
